The paper deals with distributed algorithms in radio networks, which are typically studied in the computer networks (cs.NI) and distributed computing (cs.DC) communities. The focus on randomized algorithms and analysis suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the theoretical computer science (cs.DS) and information theory (cs.IT) communities. Finally, the study of broadcasting multiple messages from a single source may be of interest to the social and information networks (cs.SI) community.
